Preference-Applied

The HTTP  Preference-Applied  header informs the client about which preferences from the
<L=32> Prefer </L> request header were applied by the server.

The server indicates if a preference is applied to a response if it would otherwise be ambiguous for the
client.

  --------------------------------- -----------------
  Header type                       Response header
  Forbidden header name             No
  CORS-safelisted response header   No
  --------------------------------- -----------------

<L=33#4>Syntax</L><I=4>
http

    Preference-Applied: <preference>

<L=33#5>Examples</L><I=5>
<L=33#6>Server applies timezone preferences</L><I=6>
The following request indicates that the client prefers events to be represented in a certain time zone:

http

    GET /events HTTP/1.1
    Host: example.com
    Prefer: timezone=America/Los_Angeles

The server supports the preference and sends back the content with a  Preference-Applied  header:

http

    HTTP/1.1 200 OK
    Content-Type: application/json
    Preference-Applied: timezone=America/Los_Angeles

    [
      {"t":"2023-10-18T05:37:59.611-07:00"},
      {"t":"2023-10-18T07:37:59.611-07:00"},
      {"t":"2023-10-18T09:37:59.611-07:00"}
    ]

<L=33#7>Specifications</L><I=7>
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Specification
  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
  Unknown specification
  # section-3

  --------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

<L=33#8>See also</L><I=8>
-   <L=32> Prefer </L>
-   Prefer header on docs.oasis-open.org
-   Prefer header on docs.postgrest.org
This page was last modified on Mar 28, 2025 by MDN contributors .

