X-Forwarded-Host

The HTTP  X-Forwarded-Host  (XFH) request header is a de-facto standard header for identifying the
original host requested by the client in the <L=28> Host </L> HTTP request header.

Host names and ports of reverse proxies (load balancers, CDNs) may differ from the origin server handling
the request, in that case the  X-Forwarded-Host  header is useful to determine which  Host  was
originally used.

A standardized version of this header is the HTTP <L=26> Forwarded </L> header, although it's much less
frequently used.

  -------------------------- ----------------
  Header type                Request header
  Forbidden request header   No
  -------------------------- ----------------

<L=4e#4>Syntax</L><I=4>
http

    X-Forwarded-Host: <host>

<L=4e#5>Directives</L><I=5>
 <host> 

    The domain name of the forwarded server.

<L=4e#6>Examples</L><I=6>
http

    X-Forwarded-Host: id42.example-cdn.com

<L=4e#7>Specifications</L><I=7>
Not part of any current specification.

<L=4e#8>See also</L><I=8>
-   <L=4d> X-Forwarded-For </L> , <L=4f> X-Forwarded-Proto </L> headers
-   <L=28> Host </L>
-   <L=26> Forwarded </L>
